Edition:
Quote:  This was the season when the fruit of the `tutu' or `tupakihi', as it is called in the North Island, was ripe. <i>Ibid.</i>  Jan 9 in 1851 Shortland Southern Districts of NZ 195-196 These plains are called `pakihi,' a word used in the North Island to signify dried up. So that `tupakihi,' the name by which the `tutu' is there known, appears to be a contraction of `tutupakihi,' or `tutu' of the [196] plains, which are well called `pakihi,' being for the most part arid.
Notes:  1844 Jan 8 in 1851 Shortland Southern Districts of NZ 191

